description:
lora_l2.c:362-371 uses magic numbers 100 and RX_TIMEOUT_MS for join timeouts:
```c
int join_ret = k_thread_join(&rx_thread_data, K_MSEC(100));
if (join_ret == -EAGAIN) {
    join_ret = k_thread_join(&rx_thread_data, K_MSEC(RX_TIMEOUT_MS));
```

The comment at 357-361 explains the rationale (100ms for common case, then RX_TIMEOUT_MS for blocked-in-lora_recv case), but the 100 appears unexplained in the code itself.

What goes wrong: Someone tuning timeouts might not understand why 100ms was chosen or that it relates to 'not blocked in lora_recv'.

Suggested:
```c
#define RX_THREAD_QUICK_JOIN_MS 100  /* Thread not blocked in lora_recv */

int join_ret = k_thread_join(&rx_thread_data, K_MSEC(RX_THREAD_QUICK_JOIN_MS));
```
